    <text>
        <body>
            <head>136. Memorandum From <persName corresp="rectu0ilGsuuTnBLm">Gary Sick</persName> of
                the <orgName corresp="recft7WGb7Fww0wma">National Security Council</orgName> Staff
                to the President’s Deputy Assistant for National Security Affairs (<persName
                    corresp="recHKbRV17rB9OSQC">Aaron</persName>)<note n="1" place="foot"
                    type="source" xml:id="d136fn1">Source: Carter Library, National Security
                    Affairs, Staff Material, Middle East, Subject File, Box 61, Libya: 9–10/80.
                    Secret. <persName corresp="recHKbRV17rB9OSQC">Aaron</persName> wrote “Send a
                    copy to <persName corresp="recmuqw5Os9XgfmEq">Pustay</persName>” in the upper
                    right-hand corner and initialed the memorandum.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1980-09-17"
                        >September 17, 1980</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <list type="subject">
                <head>SUBJECT</head>
                <item>
                    <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName>
                </item>
            </list>
            <p>The attached is a speech which <persName corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU"
                    >Qadhafi</persName> made yesterday—the same date as the apparent hostile
                intercept of the U.S. <rs type="topic" corresp="reccKWZw7wcZPbjV8">reconnaissance
                    aircraft</rs>.<note n="2" place="foot" xml:id="d136fn2">Attached but not
                    printed.</note> The tone of the speech is bellicose in the extreme, and it lends
                substance to the seriousness of the <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH"
                    >Libyan</placeName> reaction.</p>
            <p>The last paragraph, in particular, is a virtual call for war with the United States,
                referring to the forthcoming <rs type="topic" corresp="recQZHNztoaX0AXIm"
                    >exercise</rs> as an invasion of the Arab homeland. Given the nature of this
                speech, we would probably be well advised to assume that the attack yesterday was
                real and that <persName corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU">Qadhafi</persName> may in fact
                be planning some kind of suicide mission in conjunction with our <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recQZHNztoaX0AXIm">exercise</rs>.<note n="3" place="foot"
                    xml:id="d136fn3">
                    <persName corresp="recHKbRV17rB9OSQC">Aaron</persName> underlined “some kind of
                    suicide mission in conjunction with our <rs type="topic"
                        corresp="recQZHNztoaX0AXIm">exercise</rs>,” and placed an asterisk in the
                    right-hand margin.</note>
            </p>
            <p>I have talked to <orgName corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">State</orgName> (<persName
                    corresp="reciS8viNYFKOFWI7">Draper</persName>) who is intensely aware of the
                risks. (<orgName corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">State</orgName> is having some
                psychiatrists examine <persName corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU">Qadhafi</persName>’s
                recent words and behavior on the grounds that he may have finally gone totally
                insane.) However, <persName corresp="reciS8viNYFKOFWI7">Draper</persName>
                believes—and so do I—that we should proceed with the <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recQZHNztoaX0AXIm">exercise</rs>.</p>
            <p>You may wish to have another meeting this week to go over the rules of engagement,
                military options, and risks prior to the commencement of the <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recQZHNztoaX0AXIm">exercise</rs> this weekend.<note n="4" place="foot"
                    xml:id="d136fn4">
                    <persName corresp="recHKbRV17rB9OSQC">Aaron</persName> drew a line from this
                    sentence and wrote beneath the paragraph: “<hi rendition="simple_italic"
                        >YES</hi> Set it up.”</note> We should take every possible precaution.</p>
        </body>
    </text>
